# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sprite-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:sprite-rendering/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] In computer graphics, **alpha compositing** or **alpha blending** is the process of combining one image with a background to create the appearance of partial or full transparency.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] It is often useful to render picture elements (pixels) in separate passes or layers and then combine the resulting 2D images into a single, final image called the composite.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Compositing is used extensively in film when combining computer-rendered image elements with live footage.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Alpha blending is also used in 2D computer graphics to put rasterized foreground elements over a background.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] In order to combine the picture elements of the images correctly, it is necessary to keep an associated *matte* for each element in addition to its color.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] This matte layer contains the coverage information—the shape of the geometry being drawn—making it possible to distinguish between parts of the image where something was drawn and parts that are empty.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Although the most basic operation of combining two images is to put one over the other, there are many operations, or blend modes, that are used.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The concept of an alpha channel was introduced by Alvy Ray Smith and Ed Catmull in the late 1970s at the New York Institute of Technology Computer Graphics Lab.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Wallace derived the same straight **over** operator based on a physical reflectance/transmittance model in 1981.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] A 1984 paper by Thomas Porter and Tom Duff introduced premultiplied alpha using a geometrical approach.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The use of the term *alpha* is explained by Smith as follows: "We called it that because of the classic linear interpolation formula $\alpha A+(1-\alpha )B$ that uses the Greek letter $\alpha$ (alpha) to control the amount of interpolation between, in this case, two images A and B".
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] That is, when compositing image A atop image B, the value of $\alpha$ in the formula is taken directly from A's alpha channel.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] In a 2D image a color combination is stored for each picture element (pixel), often a combination of red, green and blue (RGB).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] When alpha compositing is in use, each pixel has an additional numeric value stored in its **alpha channel**, with a value ranging from 0 to 1.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] A value of 0 means that the pixel is fully transparent and the color in the pixel beneath will show through.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] A value of 1 means that the pixel is fully opaque.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] With the existence of an alpha channel, it is possible to express compositing image operations using a *compositing algebra*.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] For example, given two images *A* and *B*, the most common compositing operation is to combine the images so that *A* appears in the foreground and *B* appears in the background.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] This can be expressed as *A* **over** *B*.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The **over** operator is, in effect, the normal painting operation (see Painter's algorithm).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The **in** and **out** operators are the alpha compositing equivalent of clipping.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The two use only the alpha channel of the second image and ignore the color components.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] In addition, **plus** defines additive blending.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] If an alpha channel is used in an image, there are two common representations that are available: straight (unassociated) alpha and premultiplied (associated) alpha.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The most significant advantage of premultiplied alpha is that it allows for correct blending, interpolation, and filtering.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Ordinary interpolation without premultiplied alpha leads to RGB information leaking out of fully transparent (A=0) regions, even though this RGB information is ideally invisible.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] When interpolating or filtering images with abrupt borders between transparent and opaque regions, this can result in borders of colors that were not visible in the original image.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Errors also occur in areas of semitransparency because the RGB components are not correctly weighted, giving incorrectly high weighting to the color of the more transparent (lower alpha) pixels.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Premultiplied alpha may also be used to allow regions of regular alpha blending (e.g. smoke) and regions with additive blending mode (e.g. flame and glitter effects) to be encoded within the same image.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] This is represented by an RGBA triplet that express emission with no occlusion, such as (0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.0).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Another advantage of premultiplied alpha is performance; in certain situations, it can reduce the number of multiplication operations (e.g. if the image is used many times during later compositing).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The Porter–Duff operations have a simple form only in premultiplied alpha.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Some rendering pipelines expose a "straight alpha" API surface, but converts them into premultiplied alpha for performance.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] One disadvantage of premultiplied alpha is that it can reduce the available relative precision in the RGB values when using integer or fixed-point representation for the color components.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] This may cause a noticeable loss of quality if the color information is later brightened or if the alpha channel is removed.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] In practice, this is not usually noticeable because during typical composition operations, such as OVER, the influence of the low-precision color information in low-alpha areas on the final output image (after composition) is correspondingly reduced.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] This loss of precision also makes premultiplied images easier to compress using certain compression schemes, as they do not record the color variations hidden inside transparent regions, and can allocate fewer bits to encode low-alpha areas.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The same “limitations” of lower quantisation bit depths such as 8 bit per channel are also present in imagery without alpha, and this argument is problematic as a result.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Assuming that the pixel color is expressed using *straight* (non-premultiplied) RGBA tuples, a pixel value of (0, 0.7, 0, 0.5) implies a pixel that has 70% of the maximum green intensity and 50% opacity.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] If the color were fully green, its RGBA would be (0, 1, 0, 0.5).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] However, if this pixel uses premultiplied alpha, all of the RGB values (0, 0.7, 0) are multiplied, or scaled for occlusion, by the alpha value 0.5, which is appended to yield (0, 0.35, 0, 0.5).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] In this case, the 0.35 value for the G channel actually indicates 70% green emission intensity (with 50% occlusion).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] A pure green emission would be encoded as (0, 0.5, 0, 0.5).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Knowing whether a file uses straight or premultiplied alpha is essential to correctly process or composite it, as a different calculation is required.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Emission with no occlusion cannot be represented in straight alpha.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] No conversion is available in this case.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] The most popular image formats that support the alpha channel are PNG and TIFF.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] GIF supports 1-bit transparency by designating one palette entry as transparent.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Support for alpha channels is present in some video codecs, such as Animation and Apple ProRes 4444 of the QuickTime format, or in the Techsmith multi-format codec.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] This transformation better utilizes the limited number of bits in the encoded image by choosing $\gamma$ that better matches the non-linear human perception of luminance.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] When combined with premultiplied alpha, pre-multiplication is done in linear space, prior to gamma compression.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Note that the alpha channel may or may not undergo gamma-correction, even when the color channels do.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Although used for similar purposes, transparent colors and image masks do not permit the smooth blending of the superimposed image pixels with those of the background (only whole image pixels or whole background pixels allowed).
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] A similar effect can be achieved with a 1-bit alpha channel, as found in the 16-bit RGBA high color mode of the Truevision TGA image file format and related TARGA and AT-Vista/NU-Vista display adapters' high color graphic mode.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] This mode devotes 5 bits for every primary RGB color (15-bit RGB) plus a remaining bit as the "alpha channel".
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Dithering can be used to simulate partial occlusion where only 1-bit alpha is available.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] For some applications, a single alpha channel is not sufficient: a stained-glass window, for instance, requires a separate transparency channel for each RGB channel to model the red, green and blue transparency separately.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] More alpha channels can be added for accurate spectral color filtration applications.
[src:sprite-rendering/alpha-compositing] Some order-independent transparency methods replace the **over** operator with a commutative approximation.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Rendering is used in architecture, simulators, video games, movies and television visual effects and design visualization.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Rendering is the last step in an animation process, and gives the final appearance to the models and animation with visual effects such as shading, texture-mapping, shadows, reflections and motion blur.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Rendering can be split into two main categories: real-time rendering (also known as online rendering), and pre-rendering (also called offline rendering).
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Real-time rendering is used to interactively render a scene, like in 3D computer games, and generally each frame must be rendered in a few milliseconds.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Offline rendering is used to create realistic images and movies, where each frame can take hours or days to complete, or for debugging of complex graphics code by programmers.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] For real-time rendering the focus is on performance.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] The technology used in these games is currently categorized as 2.5D.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] One of the first games architecturally similar to modern 3D titles, allowing full 6DoF, was *Descent*, which featured 3D models entirely made from bitmap textured triangular polygons.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Voxel-based graphics also gained popularity for fast and relatively detailed terrain rendering, as in *Delta Force*, but popular fixed-function hardware eventually made its use impossible.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] *Quake* features an efficient software renderer by Michael Abrash and John Carmack.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] With its popularity, *Quake* and other polygonal 3D games of that time helped the sales of graphics cards, and more games started using hardware APIs like DirectX and OpenGL.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Though software rendering fell off as a primary rendering technology, many games well into the 2000s still had a software renderer as a fallback, *Unreal* and *Unreal Tournament* for instance, feature software renderers able to produce enjoyable quality and performance on CPUs of that period.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] One of the last AAA games without a hardware renderer was *Outcast*, which featured advanced voxel technology but also texture filtering and bump mapping as found on graphics hardware.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] In the video game console and arcade game markets, the evolution of 3D was more abrupt, as they had always relied heavily on single-purpose chipsets.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] 16 bit consoles gained RISC accelerator cartridges in games such as *StarFox* and *Virtua Racing* which implemented software rendering through tailored instruction sets.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] The Jaguar and 3DO were the first consoles to ship with 3D hardware, but it wasn't until the PlayStation that such features came to be used in most games.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Games for children and casual gamers (who use outdated systems or systems primarily meant for office applications) during the late 1990s to early 2000s typically used a software renderer as a fallback.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] For example, *Toy Story 2: Buzz Lightyear to the Rescue* has a choice of selecting either hardware or software rendering before playing the game, while others like *Half-Life* default to software mode and can be adjusted to use OpenGL or DirectX in the Options menu.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Some 3D modeling software also features software renderers for visualization.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] And finally the emulation and verification of hardware also requires a software renderer.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] An example of the latter is the Direct3D reference rasterizer.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] But even for high-end graphics, the "art" of software rendering hasn't completely died out.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] While early graphics cards were much faster than software renderers and originally had better quality and more features, it restricted the developer to "fixed-function" pixel processing.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Quickly there came a need for diversification of the looks of games.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Software rendering has no restrictions because an arbitrary program is executed.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] So graphics cards reintroduced this programmability, by executing small programs per vertex and per pixel/fragment, also known as shaders.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Shader languages, such as High Level Shader Language (HLSL) for DirectX or the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL), are C-like programming languages for shaders and start to show some resemblance with (arbitrary function) software rendering.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Since the adoption of graphics hardware as the primary means for real-time rendering, CPU performance has grown steadily as ever.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] This allowed for new software rendering technologies to emerge.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Although nowadays the dominance of hardware rendering over software rendering is undisputed because of performance, features, and continuing innovation, some believe that CPUs and GPUs will converge one way or another and the line between software and hardware rendering will fade.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] For various reasons such as hardware failure, broken drivers, emulation, quality assurance, software programming, hardware design, and hardware limitations, it is sometimes useful to let the CPU assume some or all functions in a graphics pipeline.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Contrary to real-time rendering, performance is only of second priority with pre-rendering.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] It is used mainly in the film industry to create high-quality renderings of lifelike scenes.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Many special effects in today's movies are entirely or partially created by computer graphics.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] For example, the character of Gollum in the Peter Jackson *The Lord of the Rings* films is made completely of computer-generated imagery (CGI).
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Also for animation movies, CGI is gaining popularity.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Most notably Pixar has produced movies such as *Toy Story* and *Finding Nemo*, and the Blender Foundation the world's first open movie, *Elephants Dream*.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Because of the need for very high-quality and diversity of effects, offline rendering requires a lot of flexibility.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Even though commercial real-time graphics hardware is becoming higher in quality and more programmable by the day, most photorealistic CGI still requires software rendering.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Pixar's RenderMan, for example, allows shaders of unlimited length and complexity, demanding a general-purpose processor.
[src:sprite-rendering/software-rendering] Older hardware is also incapable of techniques for high realism like raytracing and global illumination.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:sprite-rendering/sprite-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
[src:sprite-rendering/texture-atlas] In computer graphics, a **texture atlas** (also called a **spritesheet** or an **image sprite** in 2D game development) is an image containing multiple smaller images, usually packed together to reduce overall dimensions.
[src:sprite-rendering/texture-atlas] An atlas can consist of uniformly-sized images or images of varying dimensions.
[src:sprite-rendering/texture-atlas] A sub-image is drawn using custom texture coordinates to pick it out of the atlas.
[src:sprite-rendering/texture-atlas] In an application where many small textures are used frequently, it is often more efficient to store the textures in a texture atlas which is treated as a single unit by the graphics hardware.
[src:sprite-rendering/texture-atlas] This reduces both the disk I/O overhead and the overhead of a context switch by increasing memory locality.
[src:sprite-rendering/texture-atlas] Careful alignment may be needed to avoid bleeding between sub textures when used with mipmapping and texture compression.
[src:sprite-rendering/texture-atlas] In web development, images are packed into a sprite sheet to reduce the number of image resources that need to be fetched in order to display a page.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] The term "Z-order" refers to the order of objects along the Z-axis.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] In coordinate geometry, X typically refers to the horizontal axis (left to right), Y to the vertical axis (up and down), and Z refers to the axis perpendicular to the other two (forward or backward).
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] One can think of the windows in a GUI as a series of planes parallel to the surface of the monitor.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] The windows are therefore stacked along the Z-axis, and the Z-order information thus specifies the front-to-back ordering of the windows on the screen.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] An analogy would be some sheets of paper scattered on top of a table, each sheet being a window, the table your computer screen, and the top sheet having the highest Z value.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] Typically, users of a GUI can affect the Z-order by selecting a window to be brought to the foreground (that is, "above" or "in front of" all the other windows).
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] Some window managers allow interaction with windows while they are not in the foreground, while others will bring a window to the front whenever it receives input from the user.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] It is also possible for special windows to be designated "always on top"; these are then fixed to the top of the Z-order so that (with few exceptions) no other window can overlap them.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] When dealing with visual objects on a computer screen, an object with a Z-order of 1 would be visually "underneath" an object with a Z-order of 2 or greater.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] This is the same as making "layers" of objects where the Z-order determines what object is on top of another.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] An HTML page can use CSS to specify the Z-order so that some objects can be layered over others.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] Z-ordering is also used in 3D applications to determine object visibility based on overlap from other objects.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] This confers a speed advantage to the user as the computer does not need to render unseen objects.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] In practice, of course, some objects may be only partially obscured, and this is a complication that must be taken into account.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] In early real-time 3D graphics, Z-order was applied on a per-polygon basis to avoid using Z-buffer, which was considered expensive at the time.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] In modern 3D graphics, Z-order is used for order-dependent rendering, for example with semi-transparent objects.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] It can also be used to reduce the problem of Z-fighting, by either rendering farther objects first and then using weak inequality as the depth test or, conversely, rendering front-to-back and using strict inequality.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] The actual number assigned to a particular place in the Z-order is sometimes known as the z-index.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] In particular the CSS property that sets the stack order of specific elements is known as the z-index.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] An element with greater stack order is always in front of another element with lower stack order.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] Negative values can also be used in the same manner.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] A negative value will appear behind a positive one.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] `z-index` only works on elements that have a position value (e.g.
[src:sprite-rendering/z-order] `position: relative;`) and for many coders, this one of the first things to investigate when debugging why the z-index isn't working.
